<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 8.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. </p>
  <p><strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3>Community Expertise and Perspectives</h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>8K1.</strong> Expertise of individuals with practical knowledge..</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>The landscape of maternal and child health is evolving to recognize and center the expertise of individuals with practical knowledge. These individuals - including family members, individuals with self-determination, and others who have personally navigated health care systems - possess invaluable knowledge about practical challenges and service gaps within MCH systems that can significantly enhance program development and service delivery.<sup>1, 2</sup> Involving them in program design can: </p>
    <ul><li>Identify unmet needs: Individuals with practical knowledge can unveil logistical hurdles or lack of support systems, ensuring programs address real-world issues.<sup>2</sup></li>
      <li>Tailor solutions: Informed by their background and personal experiences, individuals with practical knowledge can guide development of more effective programs that resonate with various populations.<sup>2</sup></li>
	  <li>Empower sustainability: Collaboration with individuals with practical knowledge fosters a sense of ownership. Their firsthand understanding of community needs ensures programs are both relevant and sustainable, leading to long-term impact.<sup>3</sup></li></ul>
    <p>Integrating expertise from individuals with practical knowledge enhances service delivery by:</p>
	  <ul>
		  <li>Navigating the maze: These individuals can provide invaluable guidance on navigating the intricacies of health care systems. Their experiences inform the development of user-friendly services and support systems that can improve access for and utilization by MCH populations.<sup>2</sup></li>
		  <li>Building bridges: They can connect health care providers and MCH populations, enhancing trust and leading to more effective communication and service delivery, ultimately improving patient outcomes.<sup>5, 6</sup></li>
		  <li>Creating welcoming environments: Individuals with practical knowledge can help identify and address issues associated with certain MCH conditions or community circumstances. Creating a more welcoming environment where mothers and children feel comfortable seeking care can improve outcomes.<sup>7, 8</sup></li></ul>
    <p>Research provides compelling evidence for the value of involving those with practical knowledge. Studies demonstrate that incorporating their perspectives leads to:</p>
	  <ul><li>More relevant research: These individuals can help formulate research questions that are most relevant to their communities, yielding more impactful interventions.<sup>9</sup></li>
		  <li>More effective interventions: Programs co-developed with individuals with practical knowledge are more likely to be adopted and sustained in practice settings, leading to improved outcomes.<sup>10</sup></li>
	  </ul>
    <p>To maximize the impact of expertise from individuals with practical knowledge, MCH professionals must:</p>
      <ul><li>Ensure true participation: Move beyond tokenism to engage these individuals throughout the entire program development process, from initial planning to program evaluation. This fosters a sense of ownership and maximizes their contribution.<sup>9</sup></li>
	      <li>Build capacity: Provide training and support to individuals with practical knowledge, equipping them with the skills and knowledge to effectively participate in program development. Empower them to become true partners.<sup>7</sup></li>
	      <li>Acknowledge expertise: Recognize the valuable time and expertise that these individuals contribute. Consider providing fair compensation for their participation in program development activities.<sup>11</sup></li>
      </ul>
</div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>8K2.</strong> Person-centered care perspective in systems and MCH.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Person-based care, also referred to as patient-centered care, is a core principle in achieving optimal health outcomes for mothers and children. It moves beyond a disease-focused approach to emphasize the unique needs, priorities, and experiences of each individual within the MCH context. These are the key elements of person-based care in MCH:</p>
    <ul>
		<li>Collaborative decision processes: Health care providers actively involve mothers and children (age-appropriately) in treatment decisions. This fosters trust and empowers them to participate in their own health journey.<sup>12, 13</sup></li>
		<li>Open communication: Providers encourage open communication, creating a safe space for mothers and children to express their concerns, fears, and questions. Active listening fosters trust and ensures all concerns are addressed.<sup>14</sup></li>
		<li>Community awareness: Providers strive to understand and respect the values and beliefs of MCH populations. This builds rapport and ensures health care aligns with community norms.<sup>15</sup></li>
		<li>Holistic approach: Care extends beyond the presenting medical condition. Providers consider community circumstances, family dynamics, and emotional well-being to create a comprehensive care plan.<sup>16</sup></li>
		<li>Individualized care: A one-size-fits-all approach is abandoned and providers tailor interventions and treatment plans to meet the specific needs and preferences of each mother and child.<sup>17</sup></li>
		<li>Self-direction and guidance: Providers empower mothers and children (where age-appropriate) to guide their own health needs. This fosters self-management skills and promotes long-term health.<sup>18</sup></li>
		<li>Continuity of care: Whenever possible, mothers and children should have access to consistent providers. This allows the building of trust, rapport, and a deeper understanding of individual needs.<sup>19</sup></li>
		<li>Service availability: MCH services should be available to all, regardless of language, socioeconomic status, or geographic location. This might involve offering services in multiple languages, providing transportation assistance, or utilizing telehealth technologies.<sup>16</sup></li>
		<li>Social environment: The health care environment should be welcoming and respectful of all MCH populations to encourage mothers and children to seek care without hesitation.<sup>16</sup></li>   
	  </ul>
    <p>The benefits of person-based care are:</p>
	  <ul>
		  <li>Increased adherence to treatment plans, better management of chronic conditions, and higher patient satisfaction.<sup>20</sup></li>
		  <li>Lower hospitalization rates and more efficient utilization of health care resources, reducing health care costs.</li>
		  <li>Mothers and children taking a more active role in their health and well-being.<sup>12</sup></li>
	  </ul>    
 </div>
 <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>8K3.</strong> Person-centered and family-centered care perspectives in systems and MCH.</button>
 <div class="panel">
	 <p>While historically focused on family-centered care, MCH systems now recognize multiple frameworks for valuing community expertise. Both person-centered and family-centered approaches are valuable, with person-centered care emphasizing individual autonomy and self-determination, particularly for individuals with self-determination, while family-centered care recognizes the crucial role of families in supporting health outcomes.</p>
	 <p>The elements of family-centered care are:</p>
     <ul>
       <li>Recognition that the family is the constant in the child's life while the service systems and personnel within those systems fluctuate</li>
       <li>Facilitation of parent/professional collaboration at all levels of health care</li>
       <li>Sharing of unbiased and complete information with parents about their child's care on an ongoing basis in an appropriate and supportive manner</li>
       <li>Implementation of appropriate policies and programs that are comprehensive and provide emotional and financial support to meet the needs of families</li>
       <li>Recognition of family capabilities and individuality and respect for different methods of adapting</li>
       <li>Understanding and incorporating the developmental needs of infants, children, and adolescents and their families into the health care delivery system</li>
       <li>Encouragement and facilitation of parent-to parent support</li>
       <li>Assurance that the design of health care delivery systems is flexible, available, and responsive to families needs</li>
     </ul>
     <p>The core principles of family-centered care are that:</p>
     <ul>
       <li>People are treated with dignity and respect.</li>
       <li>Health care providers communicate and share information with patients and families in ways that are affirming and useful.</li>
       <li>Individuals and families build on their capabilities by participating in experiences that enhance feelings of control and independence.</li>
       <li>Collaboration occurs in policy and program development and professional education, as well as in the development of care.</li>
     </ul>
     </div>
  
	 <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comment-1"></i> <strong>8S1.</strong> Seek and apply input from individuals with community expertise.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Gathering experiences and perspectives from individuals with community expertise can:</p>
    <ul depth="0"><li index="3">Increase service efficiency and effectiveness </li>
      <li>Reduce duplications in services or activities </li>
      <li>Enhance program and service satisfaction </li>
      <li>Improve staff understanding and responsiveness</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Because they have to navigate a variety of systems on a frequent basis, families are a valuable source of practical knowledge. Tapping into their knowledge and expertise can bring insights into how these systems can work more efficiently and effectively.</p>
    <p>Ways to involve families include:<sup>22</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Family representatives as external consultants </li>
      <li>Family representatives on staff </li>
      <li>Focus groups/structured interviews </li>
      <li>Provide input through social media </li>
      <li>Provide input through website </li>
      <li>Partnerships with family organizations </li>
      <li>Opportunities for input at public hearings </li>
      <li>Opportunities for input via public notices </li>
      <li>Representatives on advisory groups </li>
      <li>Surveys/satisfaction surveys</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Treating families as partners, rather than dependents, is an effective way to make changes at all levels of MCH — local, state, and national. However, it does require a shift in thinking about the roles of provider and patient/client.<sup>22</sup></p>
    <p>Common ways to reach families:<sup>6</sup></p>
    <ul><li>Connect with families through programs such as Early Intervention, Newborn Screening and specialty clinics </li>
      <li>Connect with families through the schools, such as families of children with an Individualized Education Program/Plan or similar </li>
      <li>Create a diagnosis-based registry/database </li>
      <li>Build question(s) about interest in participating on advisory committees into application forms and follow-up systems </li>
      <li>Partner with organizations already engaged with communities and populations of interest </li>
      <li>Recruit from different regional areas </li>
      <li>Use data to determine which families to engage in specific areas</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Sustaining meaningful engagement of families starts at recruitment, with clarity about what the program is asking of them. Provide a range of opportunities that require varying levels of time and commitment. Cultivate engagement by starting with smaller roles at first, then allowing them to grow into more deeply engaging roles over time.<sup>22</sup></p>
    <p>It is important to acknowledge the involvement of individuals with community expertise with a tangible benefit of some form. One survey of MCH organizations and those specifically serving CYSHCN found that a common financial compensation is a transportation stipend or mileage reimbursement. Other forms of compensation included:<sup>22</sup></p>
    <ul><li>Participation stipend/honorarium </li>
      <li>Child care stipend </li>
      <li>Reimbursement for mileage and per diem (per the state reimbursement rate)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-users"></i> <strong>8S2.</strong> Provide training and leadership opportunities to individuals with community expertise.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Leadership ability among individuals with community expertise can develop along different paths. Some may first find their voice as self-determined individuals or within their families, while others may move directly into community leadership roles. All paths and levels of engagement are valuable and should be supported through appropriate training, mentoring, and compensation.</p>
    <p>Some will then progress to taking on leadership roles in their community, for example at their local school or health clinic.</p>
    <p>An additional group will move into leadership roles on behalf of others who are in situations similar to theirs. They may take on a role in policy development or work on legislation that will aid other families in situations such as their own.</p>
    <p>All three levels of leadership development are valuable. However, asking or recommending that someone serve in a leadership role that exceeds their capacity will generally not yield productive results.</p>
    <p>MCH professionals can provide training and mentoring to help individuals and families progress to higher levels of leadership.</p>
    <p>The role of an individual or family sharing their unique expertise is crucial for programs to incorporate in a variety of settings. Situating parents as teachers to share their stories and experiences has been shown to be effective in building an understanding of family perspectives and increasing competency in family-centered practices.<sup>24</sup></p>
    <p>Being an individual with special health care needs, or a parent or family member of such an individual, is to have practical knowledge that could never be taught in any university course. These experiences must be deliberately incorporated into training programs.<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>There are several ways family, youth and community members can provide training and guidance:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Be hired as formal faculty</li>
      <li>Serve as curriculum coordinator</li>
      <li>Mentor trainees</li>
      <li>Serve as presenters/panelists</li>
    </ul>
</div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>8S3.</strong> Demonstrate shared decision-making with individuals with community expertise.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>When considering quality improvement, MCH professionals should shift their thinking from servicing communities to partnering with individuals with community expertise. This includes recognizing both individual and collective knowledge.<sup>23</sup></p>
        
    <p><strong>Using Shared Decision-Making</strong></p>
    
    <p>Shared decision-making occurs when individuals with community expertise and professionals work together to make decisions using evidence-based information and practical knowledge. This approach values both clinical expertise and personal/community wisdom.</p>
    <p>One shared decision-making technique is the AHRQ's SHARE Approach::<sup>26</sup></p>
	  
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Seek </strong>your patient&rsquo;s/client&rsquo;s participation</li>
      <li><strong>Help </strong>your patient/client explore and compare treatment options</li>
      <li><strong>Assess </strong>your patient&rsquo;s/client&rsquo;s values and preferences</li>
      <li><strong>Reach </strong>a decision with your patient/client</li>
      <li><strong>Evaluate </strong>your patient&rsquo;s/client&rsquo;s decision</li>
    </ul>
	  
	  <p><strong>Using a Capabilities-Based Approach</strong><sup>27</sup></p>
        
      <ul>
      <li>Assess families not just for their needs, but for their strengths.</li>
      <li>Consider challenges and capabilities of each family member</li>
      <li>Consider professional skills among family members</li>
      <li>Consider personal experience with various systems among family members</li>
      <li>Look for capabilities within the community</li>
      <li>Keep in mind the interplay between family members, the family as a whole, neighborhood and environment.</li>
    </ul>
	</div>
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>8S4. </strong> Tailor recommendations to community circumstances affecting individuals with community expertise.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Professionals working in MCH should respect and support the values, languages, and backgrounds of all individuals and communities. Services should begin with acceptance of both similarities and differences in background, ability, religion, education, income, family configuration, geographic location and other characteristics that contribute to human uniqueness.<sup>28</sup></p>
  </div>
     <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-puzzle"></i> <strong>8S5. </strong> Recognize and support the unique backgrounds of individuals and families.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Valuing community expertise and perspectives means recognizing the capabilities, traditions, and knowledge that everyone brings to respectful partnerships. This includes acknowledging that individuals and communities are experts in their own experiences and should be decision-makers at all levels - from their own care to systems and policy participation.<sup>21</sup></p>
  </div>
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-puzzle"></i> <strong>8S6.</strong> Recognize organization/system-level policies impacting individuals requiring additional health services.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Understanding how <a href="https://mchb.hrsa.gov/programs-impact/focus-areas/children-youth-special-health-care-needs-cyshcn">organizational and system-level policies affect children and youth with special health care needs (CYSHCN) </a>is crucial for MCH leaders. These policies can create either challenges or supports that significantly impact health outcomes and access to care.</p>
    <p>Key aspects to consider include:</p>
    <ul depth="0">
      <li index="0">How organizational policies affect access to and coordination of services
        <ul depth="1">
          <li index="0">Referral processes and requirements</li>
          <li index="1">Care coordination protocols</li>
          <li index="2">Eligibility criteria and documentation requirements</li>
          <li index="3">Transportation and scheduling policies</li>
          <li index="4">Language access and communication policies</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li index="1">How system-level policies influence care delivery
        <ul depth="1">
          <li index="0">Insurance coverage and payment policies</li>
          <li index="1">Transition policies between pediatric and adult care systems</li>
          <li index="2">Cross-agency coordination requirements</li>
          <li index="3">Workforce development and training requirements</li>
          <li index="4">Data sharing and privacy policies</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li index="2">Impact of policies on health outcomes
        <ul depth="1">
          <li index="0">How policies may create or reduce differences in access</li>
          <li index="1">Whether policies account for community circumstances</li>
          <li index="2">How policies address communication needs</li>
          <li index="3">Accessibility requirements for facilities and services</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>MCH leaders should:</p>
    <ul depth="0"><li index="4">Regularly assess how organizational and system policies affect CYSHCN and their families </li>
      <li>Engage individuals with community expertise in policy review and development </li>
      <li>Consider unintended consequences of policies on different populations </li>
      <li>Participate in policy changes that better support CYSHCN and their families </li>
      <li>Ensure policies promote coordination across systems of care</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Remember that CYSHCN often interact with multiple systems (healthcare, education, social services, etc.) and policies need to support integration and coordination across these systems.</p>
  </div>
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
 
 
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-building"></i> <strong>8S7.</strong> Collaborate with organizations led by individuals with community expertise.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Building relationships and contracting with organizations led by individuals with community expertise is an essential strategy for ensuring authentic engagement across all MCH programs. These partnerships should be based on mutual respect, shared power, and appropriate compensation.</p>
    <p>Here are some strategies for building relationships with such organizations:<sup>13</sup></p>
    <p> <strong>Nurture personal relationships:</strong>Though it can be challenging, work to build relationships across different experiences, styles, expectations, and perspectives to reach common understandings and develop consensus.</p>
    <p><strong>Acknowledge that the partnering process takes time:</strong> Allot enough time and resources to build and sustain partnerships. Regularly assess progress from individual, family, and program staff perspectives.</p>
    <p><strong>Commit necessary resources: </strong>To ensure ongoing partnerships, sufficient resources are needed upfront and throughout the partnership to support authentic involvement. Programs need to support the needed staff commitment.</p>
    <p><strong>Seek buy-in from all levels: </strong>It is critical that the people at the highest level of the program are committed to the partnership and value including the perspectives of individuals with community expertise in their decision-making process.</p>
    <p><strong>Be clear about expectations:</strong> Provide information, support, and defined roles. Spend time discussing expectations. Offer an opportunity for feedback on roles and expectations and listen to responses. Remember: All parties should benefit from the partnership.</p>
    <p><strong>Acknowledge responsibilities: </strong>Sort out roles and responsibilities by asking the difficult questions, "What have we agreed to?" "What do we disagree about?" Through ongoing honest communication, partners can find ways to approach problems, assess the realities of the relationship, and incorporate them into ongoing plans. Recognize that all partners have responsibility for both the process of partnering and for the end product itself. While each party bears responsibility, roles are different for the partners.</p>
    <p><strong>Plan thoroughly:</strong> Planning is crucial. It can be helpful to invite existing leaders with whom you have productive relationships to be planning partners. Brainstorm practical and philosophical issues that might arise for the program, for the agency, for the staff, and for all other partners. Examine each one of the issues from a 360-degree perspective.</p>
    <p><strong>Think through challenging issues proactively.</strong> In some cases, partners bring preconceptions, protectiveness of "turf" and suspicions. Build trust by encouraging time, open communication, transparency, and reciprocity. Transparency includes revealing limitations, competition from related objectives that may affect the partnership, and expectations around benefits and results.</p>
    <p><strong>Offer opportunities for everyone involved to express concerns: </strong>The more time and space people have to discuss their ideas and reactions (both positive and negative) the greater their buy-in will be. Create a climate where it is safe to express doubts. Encourage dialogue, be respectful of different opinions, and express optimism about the benefits of the partnership. An effective collaboration rests on securing the commitment of stakeholders at all levels of the agency and community.</p>
    <p><strong>Anticipate and address challenges: </strong>Some people may be wary of agencies; staff professionals may be uncertain about partnerships with individuals and groups without formal training; there may be worries about confidentiality, there may be a lack of resources to support partnerships. Plan to address these and other challenges that you encounter.</p>
  </div>
    
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comments-1"></i> <strong>8S8.</strong> Use feedback for quality improvement/monitoring.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>How to Gather Feedback Using Focus Groups</strong>. Focus groups are a great way to gather a large amount of information from a specific group of people. To put it simply, a focus group is an interview with six to 10 people done at the same time.</p>
    <p>Steps for Holding a Focus Group<sup>14</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li> Define the reasons for wanting to do a focus group</li>
      <li> Develop specific questions to ask during the focus group
        <ul>
          <li>Questions should be open-ended </li>
          <li>Questions should move from broad to narrow focus to allow participants a chance to get comfortable with participating. </li>
          <li>Create a maximum of 15 questions, which should take an hour and a half to discuss.</li>
          <li>Prepare additional questions to get more specific information and/or clarification on main questions.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Decide how you will recruit participants to be a part of the focus group.
        <ul>
          <li>Draw from existing lists of members/project participants</li>
          <li>Ask for community partners to reach out to their members on your behalf</li>
          <li>Tap a well-connected and engaged community member</li>
          <li>Recruit at community events </li>
          <li>Reach out via phone or face to face to recruit focus group participants</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Define logistics
        <ul>
          <li>Decide if you&rsquo;ll provide child care for participants</li>
          <li>Decide on whether you&rsquo;ll offer incentives for participants, such as cash or gift cards</li>
          <li>Offering refreshments can help attract participants, so consider these carefully</li>
          <li>If possible, record the session</li>
          <li>Set a reasonable start time, keeping in mind some participants may arrive late.</li>
          <li>Decide who from your organization will be present during the focus group, and what role(s) they will have</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="https://gucchd.georgetown.edu/products/F2F_Brief1.pdf">View more about using a focus group to guide interventions</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>How to Gather Feedback Using Community Advisory Boards</strong>. A community advisory board (CAB) provides community members with a way to be represented in research activities that affect them. They volunteer specifically to be the voice of a community and any research study participants from it. The CAB is an essential part of community-based participatory research (CBPR).<sup>15</sup></p>
    <p>CABs provide a framework that allows community members to voice concerns about and propose priorities for research that otherwise would not be addressed, and advise on research processes that are respectful of and acceptable to the community.<sup>15</sup></p>
    <p>Once a CAB has been created, an important step is to craft operating procedures to guide how the board works together to complete tasks, including setting the agenda and documenting minutes. Procedures should address how leaders are chosen to balance leadership opportunities and power within the group. The group should establish protocols for decision-making, evaluating how the CAB is functioning, and plans for sustaining the group's activities into the future.<sup>15</sup></p>
    <p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3103575/pdf/PCD83A70.pdf">View best processes for forming, operating, and maintaining community advisory boards for community-based participatory research</a>.</p>
    <p><strong>How to Gather Feedback Using Surveys</strong>. 
      A good questionnaire should be valid, reliable, clear, interesting and succinct.<sup>16</sup></p>
    <p>Develop a conceptual framework by clearly identifying the research questions and &quot;dependent&quot; and &quot;independent&quot; factors (also called variables) you plan to investigate. This can be accomplished by interviewing subject-matter experts and conducting literature reviews. This step ensures that you have not missed any important subjects to ask about.</p>
    <p>Create questions that address the subject areas appropriately. Questions can be</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Closed-ended (answered yes/no or similar)</li>
      <li>Ranked on a Likert scale (1 to 5 or similar)</li>
      <li>Open-ended (requiring a list or sentence that will need to be analyzed)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Closed-ended questions work well if the range of answers are well known and the options are limited; open-ended questions are preferred if the answer options are multiple and unknown.</p>
    <p>Think about the order in which you ask questions. Start with simple questions before moving to more complex questions. Avoid ambiguous questions and don't combine two questions into one. </p>
    <p>Survey translations should be tested by having the translation translated back into English. The portions of the original translation that do not &ldquo;translate back&rdquo; accurately should be adjusted.</p>
    <p>If possible, test the survey on a small group before distributing it to your target audience.</p>
  </div>
        <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-town-hall"></i> <strong>8S9.</strong> Ensure community expertise perspectives inform MCH development.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Families and community members are deeply affected by issues such as care fragmentation that results from lack of communication on the individual level, and ineffective and outdated health care policies and practices on the systems level. It's important to ensure that the perspectives of individuals with community expertise are included in research, clinical practice, programs and policy. The aims of these efforts are best met with the involvement of people impacted by the policies, systems and services they touch.<sup>17</sup></p>
    <p>Input from families, community members and others with community expertise can:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Increase awareness and understanding of their needs </li>
      <li>Improve planning and policies based on those needs </li>
      <li>Increase parent-professional communication and understanding </li>
      <li>Increase understanding of MCH programs by state officials, the general public, and the legislature. </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
        <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-user-md"></i> <strong>8S10.</strong> Assist care professionals implementing partnership models.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Bringing individuals with community expertise to the table as equal partners is essential. The following strategies support developing meaningful partnerships that value community expertise and perspectives:<sup>19</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Approach partnerships with individuals with community expertise personally. </li>
      <li>Have personal conversations with them to establish a genuine connection, then ask them to get involved with your work. </li>
      <li>Leverage existing community groups and partnerships, whether they be in-person groups or online. </li>
      <li>Create job descriptions for individuals with community expertise with clear, realistic roles and expectations. This can help potential partners make informed decisions about their participation. </li>
      <li>Make participation as convenient as possible. Host meetings outside of regular work hours and provide childcare on-site. Also include opportunities for engagement that don't require in-person attendance: hold meetings that individuals with community expertise can call into, distribute surveys and questionnaires they can complete, and encourage them to help promote events and share information. </li>
      <li>Help individuals with community expertise feel comfortable sharing their opinions. Encourage parents to pursue skill-building opportunities to help them develop their voice.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Four domains have been identified as important for promoting and ensuring meaningful and sustainable family engagement at the systems level. They are: representation, transparency, impact, and commitment. Each is presented here with key criteria to help organizations evaluate family engagement activities.<sup>20</sup></p>
    <ol><li>Representation: the process by which individuals with community expertise stand in for the rest of their community in systems-level activities such as needs assessment and strategic planning.  Assess this domain by asking if your organization:
        <ul>
          <li>Collaborates with family-led and community-based organizations for recruitment, training, and support of participants </li>
          <li>Provides peer mentors to help individuals with community expertise learn the skills to participate effectively and address barriers to their participation </li>
          <li>Ensures that family participants represent the backgrounds of those who receive the services provided by the organization </li>
          <li>Creates a friendly, supportive environment that welcomes the contributions each participant brings to the process </li>
          <li>Holds meetings that accommodate everyone's schedules to encourage regular attendance </li>
          <li>Compensates family organizations and individuals with community expertise for their time, expertise and the costs of participation, such as travel expenses and childcare </li>
          <li>Provides special accommodations, including arrangements for access and comfort for participants with physical disabilities, and materials in multiple languages</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Transparency: This assures access to the knowledge that allows all partners to fully participate in the process, and maximize their own effectiveness. Assess this domain by asking if your organization:
        <ul>
          <li>Partners with individuals with community expertise in all parts of the process, from brainstorming to evaluation</li>
          <li>Has at least two positions reserved for individuals with community expertise on committees, boards, and other groups with defined structures</li>
          <li>Considers involving people with dual roles (family member who is also a professional or family member hired as a representative within an organization), as long as they are able to avoid placing themselves in a position of conflict of interest </li>
          <li>Spells out and explains the meanings of acronyms and uses plain language when writing and speaking</li>
          <li>Includes individuals with community expertise from important activities or champions family perspectives </li>
          <li>Makes meeting minutes and other key materials available to individuals with community expertise, in formats they can access, in language they can understand, and in a timely way </li>
          <li>Explains confidentiality requirements carefully </li>
          <li>Provides opportunities for families and professionals to have training and support in understanding their roles and the process of engagement </li>
          <li>Helps all participants recognize their own context and perspective </li>
          <li>Works to understand the capabilities of individuals with community expertise and of the community at large, and designs activities to take advantage of those capabilities</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Impact: This describes what the organization is doing differently because it has engaged families in creating systems-level change. Assess this domain by asking if your organization:
        <ul>
          <li>Values, acknowledges, and acts upon the input from individuals with community expertise </li>
          <li>Permits individuals with community expertise to influence decisions about existing policies and programs and help select and prioritize new issues to address </li>
          <li>Allows individuals with community expertise to influence the process for how decisions are made in policies and programs </li>
          <li>Lets professional partners and individuals with community expertise explain how they contributed to improved outcomes or processes </li>
          <li>Partners with individuals with community expertise, family organizations and professionals in evaluation and improvement of family engagement activities</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Commitment: Family engagement is normalized and included throughout the activities that impact the organization at the systems level. Assess this domain by asking if your organization:
        <ul>
          <li>Embeds family engagement as a core value in the culture of the organization, expressed in written policies and unchanged with changing leadership </li>
          <li>Ensures those who have the authority mandate family engagement, including funders, payers, management, and policymakers </li>
          <li>Adequately funds family engagement; includes costs of a family engagement plan in the budget </li>
          <li>Budgets to ensure adequate staff time for implementing any changes made because of family engagement Includes individuals with community expertise as co-authors on journal articles, reports, and other publications and describes the family engagement activities that supported the work </li>
          <li>Makes opportunities to become individuals with community expertise who influence outcomes at the systems level available and accessible to a wide range of families and caregivers, supported by family-led organizations</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ol>
</div>
    
            <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-home"></i> <strong>8S11.</strong> Incorporate content about partnerships into health professions education.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Respectful and trusting partnerships between professionals and individuals with community expertise are essential for effective services.<sup>7</sup>Including various community perspectives in health education curricula provides meaningful opportunities for students to gain knowledge and practice building successful partnerships.<sup>21</sup></p>
    <p>Health education curricula provide a forum in which to provide meaningful experiences for students to gain knowledge and to practice some of the components necessary to forge successful partnerships with families and individuals with community expertise.<sup>7</sup>There are few formal measures of how extensively health professions and related curricula incorporate these models.</p>
    <p>However, there has been work done to evaluate the impact of including parent-led training programs in the field of neurodevelopmental disabilities and medical education.</p>
<ul>
  <li>An evaluation of a parent-led curriculum in a sample of medical residents found it had a lasting impact on physicians' relationships with families when surveyed two to 10 years later.<sup>23</sup></li>
  <li>Several smaller studies support the assertion that parent led training programs can have a positive impact on residents and mixed groups of medical students and residents.<sup>24</sup></li>
  </li></ul>
	  <p>Involving individuals with community expertise, such as the parents of pediatric patients, in the education of health care students and professionals can help them develop skills for collaborative person-centered care. In Australia, the Listening to Voices online education resource was found to create safe learning environments and overcome barriers to including those with community expertise in the education of health care students.<sup>29</sup></p>
	  <p>Implementing co-design principles and creative pedagogical approaches can aid development of educational resources that emphasize community expertise. Making such resources flexible and freely available online increases their utility.<sup>29</sup></p></div>
    
  
